english:
  title: A Record of the Lookout Pavilion
  author: Lee Chaem
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lee built a pavilion on Mao Hill, to the right of the marshlands—a modest structure, barely sheltering from wind and rain, with room enough only to kneel upon. No place for cups and platters to entertain guests. Yet come morning, Lee would walk forth from Pine Hall, leading his sons and grandsons with staff and sandals, passing through the waterways where arrowhead and lotus root grow, where fish and shrimp dart beneath the gaze of gulls and herons. Upon reaching the pavilion, he would bare his head, loosen his robes, sit cross-legged upon the earth, and find the world and his heart as one—body and fate both forgotten. There in that refuge between mountains and streams, his gaze wandered beyond heaven and earth themselves. The beauty of rivers and peaks, the infinite faces of wind and cloud—all revealed in a single glance. The joy of observing the wild is never exhausted.

    I have dwelt in this rusticity long now, become a man of the fields—though not in the way of the ancients who studied ritual and music. Rather, I am he who pays his taxes to sustain the noble and refined. Yet still I look to the ruler with benevolence, to ministers with respect, to fathers with compassion, to sons with expectation of filial piety, to friends with trust. Beyond these, what else dare I desire? If others should expect of me what I expect of them, I confess I fall short. Yet this is the essence of my looking upon the wild—it dwelt within me before ever this pavilion was raised.

    A path runs westward from the pavilion toward a garrison town, where travelers flow like a constant stream. Should I encounter riders of noble bearing, though I might know them well, I turn aside, lower my head, speak not a word, and let them pass. Doubtless they regard me with disdain and give me not a second glance. But when mountain monks or wild wanderers pass by, carrying their burdens, I call them to sit, sit with them in pleasant conversation, exchange words with ease and joy. Hours drift by unnoticed. When weariness comes, I rise to bid them farewell with a bow—they depart, and I do not hold them back. Returning then, I withdraw to the open fields to wander, or cast my line into quiet waters. As evening comes, I climb once more to the pavilion's height and gaze afar. Thus it continues, day after day. When duties press, perhaps I visit but once—morning or evening. When fancy strikes, sometimes two or three times in a single day.

    In all my dealings with the world, I take what others discard, embrace what others despise, and grow ever more devoted to such things. This pavilion is of that nature. Being humble and unmaintained, I fear others might tear it down for firewood. So each tenth month, I dismantle it and store the timbers. When late spring arrives, I rebuild it. The next year, I do the same. Thus I have learned that all things possess an endless capacity for renewal, while remaining free from the fear of ruin and collapse. Is this not a profound joy?
  footnotes:
    - Pine Hall (松堂) likely refers to Lee's main residence, suggesting his daily ritual of leaving home to visit the pavilion.
    - The practice of dismantling and rebuilding the pavilion each year reflects a philosophical principle of natural renewal (生生, the perpetual generation of life), avoiding both permanent attachment and the decay of fixed structures.
    - The contrast between dismissing people of power and embracing humble wanderers reveals Lee's deliberate inversion of conventional social values—a common philosophical stance among Korean literati of the Joseon period.
    - The phrase '野望之趣' (the joy of observing the wild) carries resonance with Chinese landscape poetry traditions, where retreat to nature offers spiritual transcendence beyond worldly concerns.
